200
00:13:30,201 --> 00:13:34,000
Scott: Yeah, basically he's playing Tetris, but each level is screwed up in some way.

201
00:13:35,023 --> 00:13:38,220
Rym: And it's-- It's screwed up in a way that would be funny to a gamer.

202
00:13:38,480 --> 00:13:40,740
Scott: It would be funny to someone who played Tetris.

203
00:13:40,900 --> 00:13:50,600
Scott: And you know what's the greatest part about this is it shows that that kind of thing in America is only funny to gamer nerds, the kind of people who make Katamari balls and roll them down the street.

204
00:13:51,460 --> 00:13:54,639
Scott: But in Japan, that's like prime time TV.

205
00:13:54,901 --> 00:13:55,700
Scott: Everyone finds it funny.

206
00:13:56,681 --> 00:14:00,580
Rym: Yeah, we could make all sorts of generalizations about the two cultures at this point.

207
00:14:00,660 --> 00:14:01,338
Scott: And America sucks.

208
00:14:01,860 --> 00:14:08,460
Rym: Well, I guess the best way to show-- I mean, it's so obvious that there's this link here, because look at American geek culture.

209
00:14:09,700 --> 00:14:16,740
Rym: Japanese culture and Japanese things figure very highly into many, many, many geeks' lives in America.

210
00:14:17,683 --> 00:14:20,060
Scott: Yep, mostly in the anime and video game departments.

211
00:14:20,241 --> 00:14:21,940
Scott: Not so much the role-playing game departments.

212
00:14:22,022 --> 00:14:22,698
Rym: No, not so much.

213
00:14:23,222 --> 00:14:25,139
Scott: No, but mostly the animes and the video games.

214
00:14:25,301 --> 00:14:27,580
Rym: Yeah, but those are two of the pillars of geekery.

215
00:14:27,921 --> 00:14:29,759
Scott: And also the live-action Asian cinemas.

216
00:14:30,260 --> 00:14:32,900
Rym: Yes, which also seem to overlap heavily with the former two.

217
00:14:33,160 --> 00:14:33,232
Scott: Yep.

218
00:14:34,240 --> 00:14:34,394
Scott: OK.

219
00:14:35,341 --> 00:14:44,280
Rym: Now, speaking of role-playing games, today we decided to depart a little bit from reviewing serious hardcore German board games or serious hardcore video games.

220
00:14:44,460 --> 00:14:45,799
Scott: You mean Nintendo video games.

221
00:14:45,960 --> 00:14:46,028
Scott: Yes.

222
00:14:46,941 --> 00:14:52,817
Rym: Well, someday we should do a whole show on what the words "Nintendo hard" mean to people who were born in the '80s.

223
00:14:53,844 --> 00:14:54,816
Rym: But that's a separate day.

224
00:14:56,104 --> 00:14:57,359
Rym: Today, you want to introduce it?

225
00:14:57,700 --> 00:14:57,996
Scott: All right.

226
00:14:58,800 --> 00:15:06,500
Scott: Today we are going to talk about the genre of role-playing games which are not so serious.

227
00:15:06,940 --> 00:15:28,080
Rym: Now, these range from games like Paranoia that are funny, but yet also social commentary and can be played seriously, to games like Hall that not only cannot be played, not only are the rules so utterly asinine that you cannot play them, but they were actually not meant to be played.

228
00:15:28,240 --> 00:15:31,779
Rym: They were sold as rule books that were to be read for entertainment alone.

229
00:15:32,060 --> 00:15:43,139
Scott: Yeah, I mean, sometimes when you want to do some tabletop role-playing, you want to do something serious with a fantasy, or you get a GURPS, or you get a D20 system game.

230
00:15:43,322 --> 00:15:43,899
Rym: Or a Burning Wheel.

231
00:15:44,220 --> 00:15:47,253
Scott: Or a Call of Cthulhu, or a 7th Sea, or an L5R.

232
00:15:48,981 --> 00:15:49,920
Rym: You make real characters.

233
00:15:50,663 --> 00:15:51,980
Rym: You look into the backstories.

234
00:15:52,360 --> 00:15:57,480
Rym: There's a complex rule system that actually works through the story you're trying to tell.

235
00:15:57,880 --> 00:15:59,219
Rym: And as a group, you tell your story.

236
00:15:59,440 --> 00:16:01,800
Rym: And it's usually really good, and series end takes forever.

237
00:16:02,380 --> 00:16:02,448
Scott: Yep.

238
00:16:03,200 --> 00:16:06,080
Scott: But sometimes, you get a group of people together.

239
00:16:07,165 --> 00:16:12,380
Scott: You want to do some role-playing, but you don't have time to sit around for hours making characters.

240
00:16:12,541 --> 00:16:13,300
Scott: It's late at night.

241
00:16:13,681 --> 00:16:16,180
Scott: You don't already have a campaign running with these people.

242
00:16:17,140 --> 00:16:19,600
Scott: And you're not in the mood for something serious.

243
00:16:19,984 --> 00:16:21,400
Scott: You're in the mood to laugh a whole lot.

244
00:16:21,500 --> 00:16:22,119
Scott: You're being silly.

245
00:16:22,160 --> 00:16:22,857
Scott: You're getting drunk.

246
00:16:23,500 --> 00:16:27,520
Rym: Yep, you got a heterogeneous group, or maybe not everyone knows the same systems.

247
00:16:27,961 --> 00:16:31,659
Rym: Or there are people who aren't comfortable making a D&D character on their own.

248
00:16:31,820 --> 00:16:33,540
Scott: Maybe there's people who haven't role-played before.

249
00:16:33,841 --> 00:16:35,840
Scott: You know, you got to introduce them to tabletop gaming.

250
00:16:36,580 --> 00:16:39,200
Scott: This is when you bust out the stupid game.

251
00:16:39,460 --> 00:16:42,495
Rym: Now, you might be thinking, "Oh, they're just talking about beer and pretzels

252
00:16:42,535 --> 00:16:42,798
Rym: D&D.".

253
00:16:43,602 --> 00:16:50,419
Rym: No, this is definitely one step below beer and pretzels D&D, because beer and pretzels D&D is very rules-heavy.

254
00:16:51,480 --> 00:16:51,915
Scott: Mm-hmm.

255
00:16:52,321 --> 00:16:54,580
Rym: We're talking, I mean, Kobolds Ate My Baby.

256
00:16:54,680 --> 00:16:57,680
Scott: Yeah, we're going to go over a few examples of the ones that we've played.

257
00:16:57,800 --> 00:16:58,840
Scott: There are a lot more out there.

258
00:16:59,203 --> 00:17:00,180
Scott: We just don't know a lot of them.

259
00:17:00,200 --> 00:17:02,440
Rym: Yeah, well, I mean, I've played Paranoia.

260
00:17:02,787 --> 00:17:02,938
Rym: Yep.

261
00:17:03,080 --> 00:17:04,660
Rym: And I've played Kobolds Ate My Baby.

262
00:17:04,762 --> 00:17:04,936
Rym: Yep.

263
00:17:05,261 --> 00:17:06,560
Rym: You have played Pokethulu.

264
00:17:06,821 --> 00:17:07,780
Scott: I've played Pokethulu.

265
00:17:07,920 --> 00:17:10,116
Rym: And Scott Johnson and I have read Hall.

266
00:17:11,262 --> 00:17:14,579
Rym: I have never met a human being who has tried to play Hall.

267
00:17:15,063 --> 00:17:16,239
Scott: I'm sure we'll find one.

268
00:17:17,021 --> 00:17:31,520
Scott: If any of you out there have played Hall, you will get some sort of non-monetary-- All right, so before we go and talk about some of the actual games themselves, let's talk about a few things that are common across the board in this genre of non-serious role-playing.

269
00:17:31,761 --> 00:17:34,640
Rym: Even though there are great exceptions to probably everything we're about to see.

270
00:17:34,640 --> 00:17:34,836
Scott: There are.

271
00:17:35,160 --> 00:17:39,540
Scott: But in general, the rules of all these games are very simple, you know?

272
00:17:39,580 --> 00:17:42,440
Rym: Or very complex, but not really.

273
00:17:42,900 --> 00:17:46,879
Scott: Yeah, like if they're complex, they're not actually complex.

274
00:17:47,520 --> 00:17:49,860
Scott: They're just, they seem complex, you know?

275
00:17:50,060 --> 00:17:52,860
Scott: Like, they'll just make up crazy bat shit, you know?

276
00:17:52,980 --> 00:17:56,180
Scott: But playing the game isn't actually difficult or time consuming.

277
00:17:56,762 --> 00:17:58,140
Scott: It's just crazy to be silly.

278
00:17:58,400 --> 00:18:01,139
Scott: It's not actually crazy difficult, like, you know.

279
00:18:01,461 --> 00:18:07,496
Rym: Yeah, actual events in the game will usually come down to something like, "Roll a D6, oh, you catch on

280
00:18:07,697 --> 00:18:08,119
Rym: fire."

281
00:18:08,445 --> 00:18:08,959
Rym: Exactly.

282
00:18:09,543 --> 00:18:11,320
Rym: Or, "Everyone points at someone.

283
00:18:11,360 --> 00:18:12,774
Rym: "and whoever got pointed at the most

284
00:18:12,976 --> 00:18:13,360
Rym: dies.".

285
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:27,872
Scott: These games are generally very, very simple to play and someone who's never played a role-playing game before can pretty much pick it up, read the book in about, I don't think I've ever seen a book for any of these games that was meant to be played.

286
00:18:27,892 --> 00:18:29,899
Scott: that takes, you know, too long to read.

287
00:18:30,202 --> 00:18:32,660
Rym: I mean-- I never even looked at the book, The Cobalt's Ate My Baby.

288
00:18:32,840 --> 00:18:34,399
Scott: Yeah, The Cobalt's Ate My Baby.

289
00:18:34,620 --> 00:18:38,540
Scott: I mean, there's one, there's a hardcover one you can buy, but I have the original one here.

290
00:18:38,701 --> 00:18:39,979
Scott: At least I think it's the original one.

291
00:18:40,240 --> 00:18:41,999
Scott: It's just a little orange pamphlet, baby.

292
00:18:42,700 --> 00:18:46,740
Scott: It's smaller than a Passover Seder booklet, a Haggadah.

293
00:18:47,243 --> 00:18:49,718
Scott: If you're a Jew, you know what that is and it's a small little book.

294
00:18:50,841 --> 00:18:53,934
Scott: It's basically a brochure if you really wanna get right down to it.

295
00:18:55,604 --> 00:19:06,240
Rym: Now, another big thing about these games that in many cases, they're designed so that the only person who actually needs to have even ever seen the rule book is the person running the game.

296
00:19:07,120 --> 00:19:09,439
Rym: I mean, Cobalt's Ate My Baby, especially Paranoia.

297
00:19:09,924 --> 00:19:19,830
Rym: You can play Paranoia seriously where everyone knows their stuff and everyone makes a character, but most games of that are run where one guy says, "I'm gonna run a game of

298
00:19:19,850 --> 00:19:20,436
Rym: Paranoia.".

299
00:19:20,921 --> 00:19:22,555
Rym: Five other people say, "What's

300
00:19:22,615 --> 00:19:23,180
Rym: Paranoia?".

301
00:19:23,502 --> 00:19:25,054
Rym: And then the first guy says, "Sit your ass

302
00:19:25,095 --> 00:19:25,437
Rym: down.".

303
00:19:26,002 --> 00:19:30,380
Scott: Yeah, that's one big thing about it is you're playing D&D, a D20 system game.

304
00:19:30,500 --> 00:19:33,280
Scott: Anyone who's playing kinda needs to know how to play.

305
00:19:33,440 --> 00:19:38,040
Scott: I mean, they have to know what spells they have available or else how do they know that they can cast them.

306
00:19:38,080 --> 00:19:40,499
Scott: They have to know what actions are available for them to take.

307
00:19:41,382 --> 00:19:45,199
Scott: They have to know when they roll a D20, what numbers should they add to it.

308
00:19:45,240 --> 00:19:47,260
Scott: so they report the correct number to the DM.

309
00:19:47,760 --> 00:19:50,360
Rym: - Yep, or the exact opposite, which is just as tedious.

310
00:19:50,860 --> 00:19:55,940
Rym: Everyone has to role play really, really well and play a really story-driven game.

311
00:19:56,021 --> 00:19:57,379
Rym: that takes a lot out of you mentally.

312
00:19:58,780 --> 00:20:02,340
Scott: - In these sorts of games, the player doesn't have to know anything.

313
00:20:02,540 --> 00:20:07,220
Scott: The DM will command them to roll dice and then tell them what happens as a result.

314
00:20:08,201 --> 00:20:14,099
Scott: Players basically just say whatever they wanna do and something works out because it's lighthearted and no one cares.

315
00:20:14,960 --> 00:20:33,040
Rym: - Another big hallmark of these games is that they are often not directly competitive, but definitely there is some form of competition either among the players or the situation where it is the Dungeon Master versus the players as opposed to it is the Dungeon Master facilitating role playing for the players.

316
00:20:33,760 --> 00:20:36,198
Scott: - Yes, it is always quite amusing to.

317
00:20:36,238 --> 00:20:45,080
Scott: you know, where the DM can control you know, many, many silly things and create lots of humorous situations which the players must fight.

318
00:20:46,503 --> 00:20:48,540
Scott: You know, it really depends, but yeah.

319
00:20:48,940 --> 00:20:52,979
Rym: - Yeah, when there's four kobolds and one baby, you can bet that one of those PCs is going to get killed.

320
00:20:53,180 --> 00:21:01,260
Scott: - Yeah, that is the, I say the chief hallmark of this genre of game is frequent and repeated player death.

321
00:21:02,140 --> 00:21:06,080
Rym: - And not along the line, I mean in most role playing systems, death is this big deal.

322
00:21:06,802 --> 00:21:07,454
Rym: My character died.

323
00:21:08,280 --> 00:21:12,000
Scott: - There are people who consider dying in D&D to be losing.

324
00:21:12,800 --> 00:21:15,098
Scott: I mean for people who think you can win and lose at D&D.

325
00:21:16,040 --> 00:21:19,600
Rym: - Yeah, we've known some people over the years who couldn't deal with a character dying.

326
00:21:20,340 --> 00:21:22,700
Rym: But then there are people, I mean they just take it really seriously.

327
00:21:22,880 --> 00:21:30,080
Rym: A character dies and they treat it like a character in an anime they've been watching for two years died or a relative died in some cases.

328
00:21:30,600 --> 00:21:37,140
Scott: - Yeah, but in these games, you pretty much die and respawn or die and make a new character all the time.

329
00:21:37,420 --> 00:21:49,160
Rym: - In fact, in many cases, silliness is often encouraged to the point that a character will put themself in a situation knowing that they're going to die expecting some sort of hilarity to ensue.

330
00:21:49,841 --> 00:21:50,951
Scott: - Yes, that is how we...

331
00:21:52,320 --> 00:21:55,380
Rym: - These games are games where characters will often die on purpose.

332
00:21:55,921 --> 00:22:00,739
Scott: - Yep, they'll die for great justice and for the great humor of everyone else.

333
00:22:01,961 --> 00:22:09,520
Scott: - All right, let's start talking about Cobalt's Ate My Baby, which has a tagline of the beer and pretzels role playing game.

334
00:22:09,720 --> 00:22:11,740
Scott: They're saying the as if it's the only one.

335
00:22:12,382 --> 00:22:15,240
Rym: - Yeah, no I think the beer and pretzels is Hackmaster.

336
00:22:15,640 --> 00:22:17,118
Scott: - It could be, it could be.

337
00:22:17,500 --> 00:22:22,640
Rym: - Even though Hackmaster, when I read it, I actually thought it was fake and that no one played it.

338
00:22:22,700 --> 00:22:25,820
Rym: And the fact that people play it really frightens me a little bit.

339
00:22:26,360 --> 00:22:29,260
Scott: - Yeah, but anyway, Cobalt's Ate My Baby is really simple.

340
00:22:29,401 --> 00:22:38,780
Scott: I mean, you make a Cobalt, which has six stats, strength, dex, agility, speed, com, I forget what com is, combat and intelligence.

341
00:22:39,160 --> 00:22:43,220
Rym: - Now it's a lot like D&D at first in that you have these stats and you roll them up and you play.

342
00:22:43,920 --> 00:22:49,240
Rym: The difference is that the Cobalt's, the way you generate them, are weak as shit.

343
00:22:49,640 --> 00:22:50,680
Scott: - Yeah, they're basically nothing.

344
00:22:51,301 --> 00:22:55,400
Scott: I mean, you roll a bunch of random stats for your Cobalt, but really?

345
00:22:55,780 --> 00:23:03,512
Rym: - Like if it were D&D, imagine if you were a character who has one hit point and has a rusty dagger that can do 0D4 damage.

346
00:23:05,200 --> 00:23:12,800
Scott: - Yeah, every Cobalt has four skills by default, which is climb, hide, cook, and tumble.

347
00:23:12,944 --> 00:23:13,438
Scott: I got hiccups.

348
00:23:14,581 --> 00:23:16,379
Scott: And then they get two more random ones, I think.

349
00:23:17,180 --> 00:23:17,818
Scott: You have traits.

350
00:23:18,180 --> 00:23:24,600
Scott: Every Cobalt has the trait of bark like a Cobalt and heightened sense of smell, but then they get another random trait.

351
00:23:25,182 --> 00:23:27,739
Scott: And they have bogeys, which are sort of like negative traits.

352
00:23:28,101 --> 00:23:33,940
Scott: And every Cobalt has Fearless and tastes like chicken, 'cause Cobalt's tastes like chicken.

353
00:23:35,342 --> 00:23:37,419
Scott: And they get a random bogey, I guess.

354
00:23:38,362 --> 00:23:41,939
Scott: And you get weapons and armor and equipment and magic and all that kind of good stuff.

355
00:23:42,500 --> 00:23:45,999
Rym: - The basic premise of the game is that you as the PCs are all Cobalt's.

356
00:23:46,705 --> 00:23:47,900
Rym: You want to eat babies.

357
00:23:48,140 --> 00:23:49,180
Scott: - Well, you don't want to eat babies.

358
00:23:49,220 --> 00:23:55,459
Scott: You want to get babies for the King Cobalt to eat at the ball or something like that.

359
00:23:55,580 --> 00:23:56,279
Rym: - Yeah, well, you have to--.

360
00:23:57,062 --> 00:23:59,140
Scott: He is having a party and he wants to have it tomorrow.

361
00:23:59,340 --> 00:24:01,600
Scott: You need babies, big fat, tasty human babies.

362
00:24:02,643 --> 00:24:08,220
Rym: - So your goal is to bust into this village full of humans with big swords and pointy bits.

363
00:24:08,360 --> 00:24:09,300
Scott: - And dogs.

364
00:24:09,780 --> 00:24:10,940
Rym: - Guard dogs and--.

365
00:24:11,020 --> 00:24:11,479
Scott: - And babies.

366
00:24:12,100 --> 00:24:13,320
Rym: - Fucking hate guard dogs.

367
00:24:13,720 --> 00:24:14,637
Scott: - Yeah, yeah.

368
00:24:16,242 --> 00:24:19,240
Scott: And you gotta get the babies and get them out.

369
00:24:19,960 --> 00:24:27,479
Rym: - Now, basically, if a human sees you, your options are basically die or die in a funny way.

370
00:24:29,401 --> 00:24:32,620
Scott: - Or don't die, but then die afterwards.

371
00:24:33,460 --> 00:24:35,200
Scott: Delay death is another option.

372
00:24:35,520 --> 00:24:41,420
Rym: - Yeah, and wasn't there some sort of system of points where whoever brings back the most babies wins and all sorts of weird stuff.

373
00:24:41,500 --> 00:24:48,655
Scott: - Yeah, there's combat between the DM, who is called the mayor of the town 'cause he controls the townsfolk?

374
00:24:48,696 --> 00:24:52,520
Scott: and such, to prevent the kobolds from getting enough babies.

375
00:24:52,740 --> 00:24:57,699
Scott: There's also competition between the kobolds to get more babies than each other and all that sort of stuff.

376
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:10,779
Scott: And, you know, let's see, the default map has, what is this, 19 squares and each square contains, is a five by five grid of spots to stand on.

377
00:25:11,482 --> 00:25:15,839
Scott: And then in the back of the book, there is flavor text for all the different squares to tell you what's there.

378
00:25:16,680 --> 00:25:24,360
Rym: - You know what, that's really another hallmark of games like that, in that in a normal game, the DM creates this vast world for you and he describes everything and you really get in the mood.

379
00:25:25,161 --> 00:25:30,299
Rym: This is the kind of game where the players will say, all right, I go to the village, give me some flavor text.

380
00:25:30,940 --> 00:25:40,679
Scott: - Yep, exactly, and the flavor text is all there and it's really, you know, you don't have to be a good DM to run one of these things because generally the book is all you need.

381
00:25:41,141 --> 00:25:50,140
Scott: And that is a problem sometimes because you're relying on the humor of the author of the book to make this an enjoyable experience.

382
00:25:50,980 --> 00:25:56,760
Scott: And once you've, you know, used all of that stuff with the same group of people, it's not going to be funny again.

383
00:25:56,980 --> 00:25:59,553
Rym: I mean-- - We played "Cobalt's Eat My Baby" 1.5 times.

384
00:26:00,640 --> 00:26:15,420
Scott: - Yeah, I mean, you play "Cobalt's Eat My Baby" with your friends and then it's not gonna be fun to play it again unless you make a new map or you come up with new jokes, you know, but the point is the game's fun because some really funny guy wrote the game.

385
00:26:15,440 --> 00:26:16,279
Scott: Who did write this game?

386
00:26:16,920 --> 00:26:19,499
Scott: Landis and O'Neill of the 9th Level Games.

387
00:26:20,502 --> 00:26:20,760
Scott: All right.

388
00:26:20,900 --> 00:26:30,780
Rym: - Now the other fun, say, you know, you have eight friends and four of you have played "Cobalt's Eat My Baby" a bunch of times and then you play it with you four and then with these four newbies who have never seen the game before.

389
00:26:30,840 --> 00:26:31,658
Scott: - Then it's gonna be fun.

390
00:26:32,120 --> 00:26:36,060
Rym: - As long as there's one person who has never played whatever game it is, it is always hilarious.

391
00:26:36,080 --> 00:26:37,240
Rym: - But it's gotta be a good person.

392
00:26:37,300 --> 00:26:39,629
Scott: If it's a schmuck who's not into it, then it's not gonna work.

393
00:26:39,649 --> 00:26:40,560
Scott: - Well, yeah.

394
00:26:40,560 --> 00:26:45,800
Rym: I mean, we played this game with Stinky Rob and despite that, it was great fun.

395
00:26:46,060 --> 00:26:55,020
Scott: - Yep, another good idea is to, you know, you play it, you put it on the shelf and then a few years when everyone's forgotten it, you whip it out again and have the fun again.

396
00:26:55,040 --> 00:26:57,418
